>
  <p>CBT (Cognitive Behavioral Therapy) and DBT (Dialectical Behavior Therapy) are two of the most commonly recommended psychological treatments. They're related — DBT grew directly out of CBT — but they serve different populations and work in meaningfully different ways.</p>
  <p>This guide cuts through the confusion so you can understand which might be the better fit for you.</p>
  <h2>The Short Version</h2>
  <p><strong>Choose CBT if:</strong> You're dealing with anxiety, depression, OCD, phobias, or specific thought and behavior patterns you want to change. You want a structured, skills-focused therapy that typically runs 12–20 sessions.</p>
  <p><strong>Choose DBT if:</strong> You struggle with intense emotional swings, self-harm, chronic suicidality, feeling out of control of your emotions, or relationship chaos. You need both acceptance and change skills. DBT is more intensive and typically longer.</p>
  <h2>What They Share</h2>
  <p>Both CBT and DBT are:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Evidence-based</strong> — supported by extensive randomized controlled trials</li>
    <li><strong>Skills-focused</strong> — you learn specific techniques and practice them between sessions</li>
    <li><strong>Present-focused</strong> — both prioritize current functioning over extensive exploration of the past</li>
    <li><strong>Structured</strong> — sessions have agendas and goals, not open-ended exploration</li>
    <li><strong>Active</strong> — homework and between-session practice are expected</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>How They Differ</h2>
  <h3>Core Philosophy</h3>
  <p><strong>CBT</strong> is built on the idea that thoughts, feelings, and behaviors are interconnected — and that changing unhelpful thought patterns changes how you feel and behave. The emphasis is on <strong>identifying and modifying distortions</strong>.</p>
  <p><strong>DBT</strong> adds a crucial layer: the dialectical tension between <strong>acceptance and change</strong>. DBT acknowledges that people with intense emotional dysregulation often feel invalidated by pure change-focused approaches. The therapy holds both: <em>You are doing the best you can</em> AND <em>you need to learn new skills</em>.</p>
  <h3>Structure</h3>
  <p><strong>CBT:</strong> Typically individual weekly sessions (45–60 minutes). 12–20 sessions for most presentations. Homework involves thought records, behavioral experiments, and exposure exercises.</p>
  <p><strong>DBT:</strong> Full DBT includes individual therapy AND a weekly group skills training session (2–2.5 hours). Plus phone coaching between sessions. Typically runs for one year. This dual structure makes DBT significantly more time-intensive than CBT.</p>
  <h3>The Four DBT Modules vs CBT Techniques</h3>
  <p>CBT focuses on:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Identifying cognitive distortions (all-or-nothing thinking, catastrophizing, mind reading)</li>
    <li>Thought records and behavioral experiments</li>
    <li>Exposure and response prevention (for anxiety and OCD)</li>
    <li>Behavioral activation (for depression)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>DBT teaches four dedicated skill modules:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mindfulness</strong> — observing experience without judgment</li>
    <li><strong>Distress tolerance</strong> — surviving crises without making things worse</li>
    <li><strong>Emotional regulation</strong> — understanding and moderating intense emotions</li>
    <li><strong>Interpersonal effectiveness</strong> — maintaining relationships while meeting needs</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>What Each Treats Best</h3>
  <table>
    <thead><tr>
      <th>Condition</th>
      <th>Better fit</th>
    </tr>
    </tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Anxiety disorders (GAD, panic, phobias, social anxiety)</td>
      <td>CBT</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Depression (mild to moderate)</td>
      <td>CBT</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>OCD</td>
      <td>CBT (specifically ERP)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>PTSD</td>
