    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Borderline personality disorder</td>
      <td>DBT</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Chronic self-harm or suicidality</td>
      <td>DBT</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Eating disorders</td>
      <td>DBT (especially binge eating, bulimia)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Emotional dysregulation</td>
      <td>DBT</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Substance use</td>
      <td>DBT-SUD or CBT depending on presentation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Relationship difficulties</td>
      <td>Both, depending on the nature</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
  <h3>Validation</h3>
  <p>One significant practical difference: DBT places <strong>much greater emphasis on validation</strong> — the therapist explicitly acknowledging that your emotional responses make sense given your history and current circumstances, before working on change.</p>
  <p>This matters enormously for people who have frequently felt misunderstood or whose experiences were minimized. CBT, while not invalidating, doesn't make validation a central structural element the way DBT does.</p>
  <h2>Which Should You Ask For?</h2>
  <p><strong>Ask for CBT if:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your main concerns are anxiety, depression, or specific thought patterns</li>
    <li>You want a shorter, more contained course of therapy</li>
    <li>You're functioning adequately and want to improve a specific area</li>
    <li>You want to understand and change the relationship between your thoughts and feelings</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Ask for DBT if:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>You experience emotional swings that feel out of control</li>
    <li>You've engaged in self-harm or have chronic thoughts of suicide</li>
    <li>You've been told you have BPD or traits of BPD</li>
    <li>Previous therapy felt invalidating — like people kept telling you to "just think differently" without acknowledging how hard things actually are</li>
    <li>You struggle consistently with relationships or feel like you never know how to handle conflict</li>
    <li>You have an eating disorder involving bingeing or purging</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Ask for DBT-informed therapy if:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Full DBT (with the group component) isn't accessible but you want to learn DBT skills</li>
    <li>You want the validation emphasis and skills modules without a year-long commitment</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>Can You Do Both?</h2>
  <p>Yes. Some people do CBT for a specific condition and then DBT skills training for emotional regulation. Some therapists integrate CBT and DBT elements based on what the client needs. They're not mutually exclusive.</p>
  <h2>How to Find the Right Therapist</h2>
  <p>When you contact a therapist, be direct: "I'm interested in CBT" or "I'm looking for a DBT therapist." Ask specifically about their training in that modality — not just familiarity but actual post-graduate training and supervised experience.</p>
