  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p><strong>Can CBT turn into DBT if needed?</strong></p>
  <p>A therapist trained in both can shift approaches. If you start with CBT for anxiety and find that emotional dysregulation is a bigger issue, a skilled therapist will adjust.</p>
  <p><strong>Is DBT only for people with BPD?</strong></p>
  <p>No. DBT was developed for BPD but is now widely used for eating disorders, substance use, chronic depression, PTSD, and anyone with significant emotional regulation difficulties. No diagnosis of BPD is required.</p>
  <p><strong>Is CBT or DBT better for depression?</strong></p>
  <p>For straightforward depression, CBT has the most evidence and is typically the first-line recommendation. For depression with emotional dysregulation, self-harm, or chronic suicidality, DBT is more appropriate.</p>
  <p><strong>Is DBT more expensive than CBT?</strong></p>
  <p>Full DBT typically costs more because of the additional group component. DBT-informed individual therapy costs similarly to CBT.</p>
